Message: Althought I'm not a big fan of Dan Slott's writing, I think he did an incredible job here and to be honest, this is the BEST issue of ASM so far and currently one of my favorites. Sadly, Flash did save everyone's lives from RG's infectious symbiote splinters and touch but took heavily damage from RG. He wasn't just Peter's school bully or a #1 fan of Spidey, he's a mighty-damn hero! RIP Flash Thompson, you'll never be forgotten.As for Otto, if he thinks about bringing Superior Spider-Man back, I wonder this leads to Spidergeddon.
Author: architectofcomics

Message: This is definitly a good way for Dan Slott to end his entire Spider-Man run. Its was action packed, emotional, fulfilling and definitly developed everyone. Though I must admit, Doc Oct appearing as a good guy all of a sudden after he vowed revenge in Secret Empire is kinda came on a left field, but hey, what ever allows him to reform officially and possibly rekindle his relationship with Marconi, I'm all for. I just hope that the next TASM writer does things a bit differently and hopefully better than the entirty of Dans run since that guy had a tendincy to sway Peter development as a character, meaning that he would constantly allowed Peter to climb up in his life, only to push him back down, then have him climb up, then push him back down again, which was the most infuriating thing about his run as well as the constant tease about the possibility of Peter learning about his worst mistake ever. But again, as a conclusion to his run, Well Playd Dan Slott.

Message: I think Superior Spider-Man was overall pretty underwhelming. It started great, it was a very good idea, but it went south really fast mainly because of the way Otto was written and the way the story escalated to absurd levels really fast. I mean... when the comic ended Spider-Man was kind of an evil genious who had monitored the entirety of New York city, had his own army, his own mechas and an evil lair (and killed people), and no one ever seemed to care or think anything was wrong or different about him (not enough to confront him at least). It got so ridiculously over the top that it didn't work. But that doesn't make this plot twist any less effective or this particular issue any worse.This was a great 700th issue regardless of what happened next.And to everyone who thinks this "destroyed Peter Parker" somehow (who reading this comment section are apparently some people) I have this to say; No, it didn't. It didn't destroy anything. Just like Peter wasn't destroyed after OMD, or how he wasn't destroyed after the Ben Reilly affair in the 90's, or that one time he stopped being a radioactive hero and his origin was retold so he's the avatar of some spider-god or some shit like that (remember that? That's probably Spider-Man's biggest retcon and no one seems to go apeshit about it ever!). And it didn't simply because this is a character that has existed for 52 years. This is a character that has been written by more writers that anyone can name, who has been through more changes in his status quo that anybody can mention. And that's the whole point of comics, a writter comes and does whatever he/she wants with the character. Because, aside from the somewhat predefined personality (like you can't make a brooding, dark, edgy Peter Parker or an easy going jokester Batman -unless it doesn't last and the change has an explanation plotwise) there's nothing fixed. What happens to them, the adventures they live, their status quo... are kind of irrelevant. They're just background noise.This, like any other change in Spider-Man's history, made a number of changes, some lasted, some (most in this particular case) didn't. Just like any other time a writer (or the editors at Marvel) tried to do something "new and original" with the character. Because that's how comic books work. And sure, as fans we all will have nostalgia towards our favourite period of time of our favourite superhero character(s) but that doesn't mean they have to stay that way (whatever "that way" is) forever. If that was true then Peter would still be a teenager going to high school. And nobody really wants that.
Author: disqus_zeEKpNxImG

Message: I actually loved this story. The stakes were high and the writing was excellent. The build up really makes me feel like Peter is going to claim his life back and triumph as usual, but no. It really made you feel something, even if you knew Peter would come back eventually.The character development along this run from Ock was phenomenal, and I can't lie, the people who hated this story most likely hated it simply because they don't like Dan Slott and have a massive bias against him, as well as those who don't like change and always force marvel to bring stuff back to the way they were before. This story was a massive risk and paid off, and I for one am glad he did it

Message: I've actually read an interesting article about this.  In the story where Hank slapped Janet, Hank was feeling that he wasn't an important member of the avengers anymore.  He was also in trouble for lashing out against a villain who was going to surrender in a previous story.  So he decided to make a robot to attack the avengers that only he could stop (I know that that is the same plot as Syndrome from the Incredibles movie, but I swear that is what happened).However, when Janet confronted Hank about his dangerous behavior, the writer/editor of the story, Jim Shooter, later explained in an interview that he intended for Hank to accidentally hit Janet as he was gesturing towards her, but the artist of the book, Bob Hall, had misinterpreted what he wanted to do.This whole situation made me feel bad for Hank Pym.  If this whole thing had actually happened the way Jim Shooter had planned, maybe people would have been a lot more forgiving of Hank.  I think that what Shooter was trying to do was tell how serious the battles of mental illness is with many people.  I think that that would have been a really interesting topic to discuss in super hero comics.  Of course, there are other characters, such as Moon Knight and Legion who have mental illnesses as well, but Hank Pym probably wasn't handled in the best way.I'm not trying to say that Hank Pym's actions should be easily forgivable.  But other characters have been forgiven for some crazier stuff, like, I don't know, SCARLET WITCH BASICALLY KILLING (BOTH FIGURATIVELY AND LITERALLY) THE AVENGERS IN AVENGERS DISSASSEMBLED, AND FORCING MOST MUTANTS ON THE PLANET TO BE RID OF THEIR POWERS IN HOUSE OF M!!!!!!!  And she suffered from mental illnesses as well.  But does she get any crap from anyone (at least to the extent as Hank Pym)?  NO!I feel like there needs to be a lot of retcons to get characters that are considered to be bad (like Cyclops, one of my favorite characters ever), and Hank Pym to be Hero's again.  Make it so that they can be considered to be a good guy again, or at least forgiven.  They have done so much good in their lives.  And sure, they've made some mistakes.  But not so much that VENOM can be considered to be more of a good guy than them!!!!!

Message: Ok that's it. I hate most of the citizens of New York... at least when they're written this way. Okay so losing their tech and jobs is bad, but are they seriously denying the fact that it was necessary to avoid getting infected or to save the world more than once?! "You weren't there under that dome with the rest of us!" ...He doesn't have to save you ungrateful jerks time and time again, especially when you turn on him over the tiniest of thing! It's not officially his job despite his claims! He does it because that's the kind of person he is!  He helped people while globetrotting around the world! He wasn't under the dome because he was trying to keep Hydra from gaining more power! Also, you had several heroes and Kingpin aiding you, so don't act like you didn't have help! WHAT IN THE NAME OF THAT IS GOOD AND DESCENT WRONG WITH YOU ALL?!...Now that my rant towards fictional characters is done, the issue was okay. It's understandable for Peter to be down when no one acknowledges that what he did was to save lives and it's also understandable that people are angered by how they were affected. I usually try to be fair when reading comics (and I don't like ranting but that one was building up for years) so I can understand why people are angry. It's just that theses people don't acknowledge the alternatives in which they would either be zombies or Hydra basically control the internet on a global scale and have more power. Well, at least Peter is starting to feel better and the crowd's cheering for Spider-Man at the end.

Message: Actually, Spider-Man's shown more courage whenever he's faced any of the Goblins.To me, this boils down to:1) The Goblins tend to be very personal in their tactics and schemes and endanger Peter's loved ones, while Venom generally only endangers Peter himself, aside from occasionally appearing to Peter's loved ones as an indirect means of goading/threatening Peter. Peter has more fighting spirit to defend his friends and family than himself.2) Venom's abilities are tailor-suited to neutralize Spider-Man's own. While the Goblins have variously demonstrated a level of strength and stamina nearly equaling Spidey's, they're not really equipped with the exact set of "tools" to negate Spidey's strength and take advantage of his vulnerabilities.
Author: disqus_oJTgn9HBH3

Message: That he'd rather defend his friends and family than himself....a fine observation. Some of the best Spidey stories have been when there's more on the line and he realizes by failing the mission, he fails his friends or family, thus pushing himself harder. In other situations when pressed against the wall and looking grim, he constantly reminds himself that it's not just him on the line but his aunt and wife, etc....But yes, all that is why I'd be a little more freaked out facing off against the Goblins. They're not afraid to go to whatever extreme they think will hurt Spider-Man and Peter Parker alike.I think you've got it on the powers-negation. Spidey has never had any kind of formal training or lessons so far as I know, he essentially donned his costume and went on his way, learning to trust in his spider-sense; it's always been there to look out for him and keep him from getting himself killed. With Venom (and other symbiotes) negating the sense, it leaves Spidey at a severe disadvantage, of detection and combat....and perhaps too Spidey's afraid of looking at what the darker version of himself would be like.

Message: So wait, among the list of reasons not to betray America to the Red Skull, Spider-Man picks patriotism? What about saving the lives that would be lost senselessly in the ensuing international conflict, crushing the Skull for being an unrepentant Nazi war criminal, or retribution for those lives that the Skull's scheme already destroyed? Besides, one could bring up that, if the U.S. were to be economically ruined, that mil would be worth as much as the ashes from the Skull's cigarette holder anyway. There should have been better reasons mentioned than just "AMERICA FUCK YEA!" for not taking the bribe.Continuity fun fact, this is the first time that the Red Skull has met Spider-Man (at least in his own titles), but this is the second time that Spidey has met the Skull. In Amazing Spider-Man Annual #5, Spider-Man fought the Communist Red Skull of the 1950's. This is the original and better-known Nazi version, though Spider-Man didn't know there was a difference between the two at this point.Speaking of which, would there be any conflict in Spider-Man's mind about taking a bribe from the monstrosity that Spider-Man believes at this point in time killed his parents?!And why would a high-ranking member of ULTIMATUM, an anarchist group that wants to dissolve national boundaries, ally himself with the Skull, a Nazi who believes in a totalitarian, strongly ethno-nationalistic, Jingoistic state where people are defined as "cogs in the machine," so to speak. ULTIMATUM wants world peace and unity, right? Since when did the Skull ever want anything but despotism and tyranny?And the Watchdogs and the Resistants are supposedly a social conservative terrorist group and a mutant liberationist terrorist group, respectively. Since when would either of these guys support a Nazi who hates American values, including traditionalist ones, and mutants, who are regarded by Nazis as scum.

Message: Venom cares for the innocents, but cares about his selfish desire for revenge more.He doesn't want to hurt Aunt May, ostensibly, but he will if Spider-Man breaks his rules as a means of getting the point across. How twisted. Like how Doctor Doom cares about Latveria and Valeria, but killed Valeria in the name of his petty need to prove himself superior to Reed Richards. Or how Magneto is friends with Charles Xavier but will kill his X-Men and destroy Xavier's dream in order to realize his vision of a mutant-ruled fascist world. Virtue overcome by vice. Glimpses of a hero in someone who is unambiguously a villain.Interesting.

Message: Naww, he's wearing his wedding ring under his costume. Wonder if that gets in the way. And look at Pete, using LEDs before it was cool. Or around the time it was cool. Man, MJ's been off modeling more than she's been around. Payback maybe for all of his disappearance acts (Kraven, nuthouse)? Bit spiteful, or perhaps that's just how she's coping with being married to Spider-Man. Ooh, little blood and gore from Ock. Still kinda bugs me Joy never once suspected or accused Pete of his dual identity. I mean yeah, she accuses him of being immoral on the practice of having a deal with Spider-Man (which does bring up the question if what he does is moral, taking and selling pictures of yourself...then again, look no farther than the Kardashians...oh god. Pete is a Kardashian.)That's kinda vague, Robbie. I agree with you, but that's vague to the point of...."Hey, you suck. Find another line of work." Tough love, maybe? I thought the direction the conversation was going to go was in vain of "Hey, you're smart, witty with words, Ned's dead, wanna be a writing reporter, Clark - er - I mean Spider-er-Peter?"Hm...I wonder if Peter wants to maintain his job as a freelance photographer out of a subconscious compulsion to ensure he patrols and keeps the world safe. He uses the Shiny Logic to justify his actions, but I'd be inclined to suspect otherwise. (Shiny Logic, crime means Spider-Man stops bad guys, which leads to pictures, which leads to money which can buy shiny things)I love how all these super baddies lately, Ock, Electro, they defeat Spidey then go "Oh no, death is too good for you, Imma make you suffer!" Must be a lot of pent up rage after being beaten so many times. Which leads to the question, why take chances? If he's beaten you so many countless times, why are you so sure this isn't a fluke? But I'm happy the Doctor has restored his faith in himself.

Message: Spider-Man has to fight an angry (ex-)Herald of Galactus to the death over a misunderstanding involving pizza and mutant hysteria. What a setup. In any case, I find it curious that mutants are described as having powers "that seem like science fiction," since there are plenty of non-mutants in the Marvel Universe, like the FF and Spider-Man himself, who fit that description and also "look like everyone else." On another note, I wonder if Firelord has to threaten restaurateurs on other planets to get the same sort of immediate service he demands.
Author: jackkirby123

Message: Thank you! That's the frustrating core of the X-Men, every issue is always about them being persecuted for being a mutant, to the point of being murdered or beat up just because of it, yet people like Captain America, Human Torch, Spider-Man, they're loved and adored....or at least, not quite as severely and unanimously hated. I get it, I get it's supposed to represent cultural differences, like racism or sexism or sexual preference, whatever, just...it only works if it's universal. If all the heroes were hated and feared like that, okay, it'd work. But hating on one specific group for no real reason other than being told "they're different" seems weird. Idk, haven't read much X-Men.

Message: She's the only family he has left. Barring Mary Jane. He had the power to prevent this from happening (Be that taking the bullet or what have you.) But he didn't so this' all his fault. He has the power to keep her alive so he's going to do that, even if by all accounts he's just lugging around a body waiting to turn cold. He himself even says that May and Mary are the two most important people in the world to him. I for one would say I'd burn the earth and move the moon and stars to keep the woman who raised me safe. One More Day sucks but Peter here is making a whole slew of choices without fully considering the consequences until afterwards.

Message: I don't really understand the backlash about saying what Peter did here was bad writing and OOC; Spidey promised to follow Tony no matter what without question, that till he was put in the condition to make the choice of whether to unmask or not. At this point, Peter obviously starts being nervous, knowing what is going to happen once he does that, he wanted to refuse, he wanted to run away even after Aunt May and MJ gave him their support and in the end, he didn't run and faced his fears, not for himself, not for Tony, but for Aunt May and MJ who believed in him. Was it a stupid decision? Maybe. Will it have repercussions? Undoubtedly. But was it bad writing? No, unless everything that tries to change the status quo became bad writing when I looked away. Was Peter acting OOC? Again, knowing the process he went through and it not literally coming out of nowhere, no. It was either that or running away, betraying Tony which he considers a father figure and leaving his own family behind or maybe putting them in more danger as relatives of an outlaw. I can just say that, even if stupid, he made the choice that seemed better at the time and hoping he can handle everything that will come out of it. That said, for future readers, I suggest to make your own impressions on the matter and read all the tie-ins besides the Civil War main event. Might offer a wider picture.

Message: Styx isn't just diseased, nor does he have moments of moral clarity where he's disgusted by what he is like Morbius either. He's just a sadistic murderer, and he deserves to be put down like a dog, not like a man.I appreciate Cardiac's motives, but this character is getting overused a lot. Especially since the Punisher used to serve the role Cardiac now does. Give Cardiac his own series like you did with Cloak and Dagger, or use some restraint when putting him in the Spider-books. Jeez, it's almost as bad as the Venom craze that began to kick in around this time.I also don't understand why Stone thinks that Styx is so deserving of a life just because he's responsible for creating Styx. Styx is still evil beyond remorse or redemption! Stone still offers up innocent victims just to sustain the monstrosity he has brought into existence! If Stone wanted to redeem himself for ruining Styx's life in such a callous manner, he should have put Styx out of his misery as soon as he realized how twisted and evil Styx had become. It's the utilitarian solution. But at this point, both have such an unjustifiable body-count as contract killers that BOTH now deserve to be executed anyway.Spider-Man is the master of braindead strawman retorts. Still, if he weren't such an incurable idealist, he wouldn't be our Spidey.

Message: "It's real comforting to know that the government isn't in bed with the Kingpin."But, Spider-Man, it is. It still paid Kingy off with the golden typewriters in return for the assistance of his armed men, and it's still corrupt, seeing as how it put the victims in internment facilities for brainwashing and stole their personal property. It's just that Kingy got a bit too greedy like the snake he is and bit the government in the back to have whatever of the gold hadn't been dumped yet.As for the government keeping the golden building secret, I disagree with it on the grounds that it violates freedom of the press, denies the public their right to know what happened, and involves flagrant violation of rights in the form of "debriefing" so the people at the site "wouldn't know what they saw." In response to the utilitarian argument that letting it be public knowledge would cause panic and so this is necessary evil, I make the counter-argument that if laws punishing offenses like assault and manslaughter were more Draconian that they might exercise a greater deterrent effect, therefore allowing for a more libertarian society to exist. When repression of truth and basic human rights is condoned through utilitarianism, it always devolves into authoritarianism and finally totalitarianism. The Marvel Universe's two greatest villains, Dr. Doom and Magneto, are in part examples demonstrative of the impossibility and essential wrongness of the "benevolent" dictatorship.

Message: I honestly don't see yet why people dislike this. WOSM filler and the Spider-Man annuals of the past decade or so, with rare exception, were far worse material than this.That crap with the space-locusts was far worse than this.That goofy nonsense with the Tri-Sentinel and Captain Universe was worse and more utterly pointless than this.Anything written by Ann Nocenti is godawful and WAY worse than this.This is cliched and has some groan-worthy dialogue, but at least there's some interesting concepts. The way Peter and Ben are reacting at least makes sense within the context of past and present experiences. At least the focus is on the characters and not some new franchise Marvel desperately wants to promote or a stupid PSA.So far, my conclusion is that the readers hated this at the time because 1) the storylines were long and they had to wait a month to get the next issue of the series, whereas it only takes a button-click for me here and 2) the storylines were all multi-parters taking place across the different titles, requiring flip-flopping among several of them just to keep up with the story in a linear fashion. Also, I guess I understand that the readers might have gotten suckered into buying useless filler, whereas I can just skip something without the animus that comes from wasting time and money and move on if I think it contributes little in the long-term to the plot.

Message: I liked this, but it was bogged down by the generic 90s clichedness of the Wild Pack and the overly heroic depiction of Venom. Yes, I believe that Venom would kidnap RIchard and Mary to "protect" them and even that he would save them from that fire, but I don't believe that Venom would give up his grudge against Spidey just because his ex-wife talked some sense into him.Venom's psychosis is that he pays lip-service to the concept of "with great power must come great responsibility," but Venom is essentially incapable of taking responsibility for his own mistakes, just projecting them onto others so that he can use his power to punish those he makes responsible, in this case Spider-Man. As Spider-Man stated in a recent WOSM tale with Venom, he talks about protecting the innocent, but he really lives to kill and slaughter, deluding himself into thinking he's a hero in order to provide himself with the excuses he needs to rationalize his vile actions.And also, why would the Wild Pack's contract say "dead or alive" if they were hired to capture Venom for a Daily Bugle exlusive. Dead men tell no tales, especially not to newspapers.

Shocker's such a coward I would never believe he'd stand up to Scourge by himself, even with enhanced power.And that doesn't even look like him on the second-to-last page! Shocker's supposed to look like a balding 50-something loser that you might think would be in charge of a failing deli or an ice-cream parlor or something.Also, Peter's comment about not even knowing his parents can't be reconciled well with the revelation that his habitual guilt-tripping comes from his parents' death moreso than his uncle's or the auditory hallucinatory flashback showing that Peter was at least old enough to converse with Uncle Ben when his parents died, all from The Child Within. And Michelenie referenced the Funeral Arrangements story that happened right after then in (PP)TSSM, so there's really no excuse. And what does the sequel to the Gang War storyline from '87 running in WOSM at the time of this issue's publication have to do with Aunt May's troubles with the Vulture? That second asterisk for the WOSM reference on page 9 shouldn't be there!Still see that Jameson's got the Wild Pack on retainer ever since that time Doc Ock tried to blow up his building and kidnap his wife. So why didn't he call them up when Carnage broke into his office?! I mean, they would've gotten slaughtered, but it would have been a sensible decision.Don't see the merit in advertising this as a "sequel" to Deadly Foes of Spider-Man just because Shocker's in it and mentions something of what happened in that miniseries.
